                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.62/63a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-08T16:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 8, 1919, 4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3374. Confidential for Polk.</p>
                <p>Department and the British Embassy here have recently agreed through an exchange
                    of notes<note n="9" xml:id="d183fn9">Not printed.</note> to open diplomatic
                    intercourse at Berlin when the moment arrives through Chargé d’Affaires [<hi
                        rend="italic">sic</hi>] rather than by the immediate appointment of
                    Ambassadors. I cannot think of any one in the service more suitable to act for
                    us in this capacity than Ellis Dresel. If you agree, will you sound him on your
                    own initiative and not at the Department’s suggestion as to whether such a
                    detail would be acceptable?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
